	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The UNDP ‘Human Development Report’ criticises EU-ACP fisheries agreements</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 September 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> The 2005 issue of the UNDP <i>Human Development Report</i>, published in September, contains a critique of the lack of coherence between the Senegal-EU fisheries agreement and cooperation and development objectives.</p><p> The report describes first how ‘development of a fisheries export industry has been supported by the French Development Agency, which has financed about one-third of the costs associated with meeting EU food-safety standards. EU trade preferences have protected Senegal from low-cost competition. Other EU donors, along with the World Bank, are supporting projects to improve Senegal’s capacity to manage fish stocks on a sustainable basis. The EU is spending $12 million to support inspection and monitoring’.</p><p> However ‘While one part of EU aid and trade policy aims to support sustainable resource management and to balance export growth with local market needs, another part is undermining these very objectives. Since 1979 the EU has financed a series of agreements that give European vessels access to Senegal’s fish stocks ... Stocks have been severely depleted, disrupting the artisan sector, pushing up fish prices in local markets and jeopardising supplies to canning factories producing for export ... Like earlier agreements, the current arrangement puts no limit on harvesting. And since there are no tonnage records, Senegalese authorities are unable to monitor stocks.’</p><p> The report concludes that ‘The upshot is that the EU is systematically undermining the development of a fish-resource management system. All of this rests uneasily with policy-coherence objectives set out in the Treaty of Rome’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> UNDP, <i>Human Development Report</i> 2005 (page 145)</p><p>

<a href="http://hdr.undp.org/reports/global/2005/pdf/HDR05_chapter_4.pdf" target="_self">http://hdr.undp.org/reports/global/2005/pdf/HDR05_chapter_4.pdf</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> To assert, as the UNDP report does, that in the main the problems in ACP fisheries, particularly those in west Africa, are caused by EU-ACP bilateral FPAs, is quite unjustified. Provided they are designed and implemented with transparency, accountability and stakeholders’ participation, these agreements should, on the contrary, provide scope for solutions that favour sustainable development.</p><p> For example, the UNDP report highlights that, ‘like earlier agreements, the current arrangement puts no limit on harvesting’. Although it is true that no quota limits are set for what the EU catches, it must be acknowledged that, for a quota system to be efficient, it would have to be enforced by the Senegalese authorities for all fleets active in their waters. However, quota systems in mixed fisheries have shown their limitations in other parts of the world. For highly diverse tropical fisheries such as those in west Africa, managing (and regulating) fishing capacity and effort is probably more suitable. On that basis, it should be noted that in the EU-Senegal agreement, the number of licenses for EU vessels is clearly defined and the vessels fishing under the agreement have to provide catch statistics to the Senegalese authorities. This is not the case for foreign boats fishing outside the EU agreement, whether from an EU origin or from other distant-water nations.</p><p> The fact remains that the EU fleets, in west African countries like Senegal and Mauritania, are catching, for EU market, species that could be fished locally by existing fishing vessels. The situation is particularly bad in Mauritania, where there is direct and intense competition between EU vessels, national trawlers, and pirogues, for over-fished octopus resources.</p><p> The possibilities to have joint ventures in the processing and marketing sectors could help to support the fish exploitation by existing local fishing vessels. These resources could be processed and exported with a view to increase benefits accruing locally through adding value.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
